# To hold as hostage.
## To have possession or [[custody]] of (a person) as [[security]] for [[performance]] against a [[treaty]], a [[pledge]], or a [[demand]], especially now an extra-legal demand.
## To seek advantage in a situation by threatening the well-being or success of (a person or thing not directly involved in the situation).
##*{{quote-book|en|title=Congressional Record: Proceedings and Debates {{...}}| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ItnywjbTB0sC| year=1996| passage=Mr. President, when someone holds up this bill and holds it hostage, it is '''holding hostage''' the money that would go to aid victims of disaster.}}
